paper/review/rendered.txt-27-1 Introduction
paper/review/rendered.txt:28:MacKenzie Scott gave away $7.17 billion in 2025 (Huddleston 2025); Giving USA counts $6.65
paper/review/rendered.txt-29-billion of it against $19.2 billion in U.S. megagift dollars — about a third of that year’s megagift
paper/review/rendered.txt-30-value (Indiana University Lilly Family School of Philanthropy 2026; Gamboa 2026). (The bases
paper/review/rendered.txt-31-differ: Yield Giving’s own annual total is the larger figure.) Her disclosed lifetime total is $26.39
paper/review/rendered.txt-32-∗
--
paper/review/rendered.txt-42-it is denominated in health, and, to my knowledge, no published estimate prices the portfolio in
paper/review/rendered.txt-43-outcomes of any kind.
paper/review/rendered.txt-44-This paper does so in the unit health economists use to compare a death averted against years
paper/review/rendered.txt-45-lived in better health: the quality-adjusted life-year. The exercise is deliberately in the style
paper/review/rendered.txt:46:of a charity evaluator’s cost-effectiveness analysis (GiveWell 2026), scaled from a program to a
paper/review/rendered.txt-47-portfolio, with one addition the setting forces: because most of the portfolio funds interventions
paper/review/rendered.txt-48-whose health effects have never been causally measured, the model makes its epistemics explicit.
paper/review/rendered.txt-49-Every effect is shrunk toward zero in proportion to how well its supporting study identifies
paper/review/rendered.txt-50-causation, the shrinkage schedule is a slider rather than a buried constant, and the headline
paper/review/rendered.txt-51-is reported across the full range of evidence philosophies — from counting only randomized
paper/review/rendered.txt-52-evidence to taking every published estimate at face value.
paper/review/rendered.txt-53-The paper makes four contributions. It provides what I believe is the first outside, portfolio-level
paper/review/rendered.txt-54-cost-effectiveness estimate of an individual mega-donor’s disclosed lifetime giving — funder-run
paper/review/rendered.txt:55:portfolio metrics exist, including GiveWell’s aggregate impact estimates (GiveWell 2026), Robin
paper/review/rendered.txt:56:Hood’s benefit–cost framework (Robin Hood Foundation 2025), the Constellation Fund’s portfolio
paper/review/rendered.txt-57-reporting (Constellation Fund 2025), and social-rate-of-return analysis of USAID’s Development
paper/review/rendered.txt-58-Innovation Ventures portfolio (Center for Effective Global Action 2023); the difference here is
paper/review/rendered.txt-59-independence from the donor, a subject who publishes no outcome data, and explicit evidence
paper/review/rendered.txt-60-weighting: a best-guess median of 202,000 QALYs from $26.39 billion nominal ($30.3B in
paper/review/rendered.txt:61:2026 dollars), a blended $150,067 per QALY, and a median benefit–cost ratio of 4.9 under the
paper/review/rendered.txt:62:HHS regulatory value-per-QALY distribution (Kearsley 2026). It estimates extreme geographic
paper/review/rendered.txt-63-concentration of impact under its pricing assumptions: the 4.8% of dollars funding global health
paper/review/rendered.txt-64-and development delivered outside the United States accounts for 69.1% of estimated health
paper/review/rendered.txt-65-impact. It reports a new empirical regularity in the gift data itself: across 1,313 disclosed
paper/review/rendered.txt-66-gift–filing pairs, gift size scales with recipient pre-gift revenue to the power 0.41 (R² 0.37) —
--
paper/review/rendered.txt-149-published estimates, and multiplies the implied QALYs by two independent discounts. Causal
paper/review/rendered.txt-150-credibility asks whether the measured effect is real. Each archetype carries the identification
paper/review/rendered.txt-151-tier of its best supporting evidence, and the tier sets a Beta-distributed shrinkage factor toward
paper/review/rendered.txt-152-the null: a lottery-randomized wealth shock (Cesarini et al. 2016) or the Medicaid mortality
paper/review/rendered.txt:153:quasi-experiments — the ACA expansions (Miller et al. 2021), with cost–benefit arithmetic
paper/review/rendered.txt:154:from the pre-ACA state expansions (Sommers 2017) whose spending component draws on the
paper/review/rendered.txt:155:Oregon Health Insurance Experiment (Finkelstein et al. 2012) — keeps most of its effect;
paper/review/rendered.txt:156:replicated child-targeted cash quasi-experiments (Aizer et al. 2016) anchor the cash bucket;
paper/review/rendered.txt-157-the community-health-center rollout design (Bailey and Goodman-Bacon 2015) and similar
paper/review/rendered.txt-158-contested quasi-experiments keep less; associational and assumption-only categories are shrunk
paper/review/rendered.txt-159-near zero. Realization asks whether a marginal philanthropic dollar delivers the studied effect at
paper/review/rendered.txt:160:all — transport to different populations, overhead, and funging, net of possible capacity effects:
paper/review/rendered.txt:161:surveyed Scott recipients report stronger capacity and reach (Buteau et al. 2023), self-reports
paper/review/rendered.txt:162:on whose basis the model permits realization above one (an author judgment, not a CEP effect
paper/review/rendered.txt-163-estimate). It is one global triangular draw with mode 0.80 on support 0.55–1.10.
paper/review/rendered.txt:164:The two multipliers are designed to partition the doubt — transportability concerns in realization,
paper/review/rendered.txt-165-identification concerns in credibility, cost-per-QALY priors stated conditional on the effect being
paper/review/rendered.txt-166-real and delivered — though the separation is imperfect at the prior boundaries: several anchors
paper/review/rendered.txt-167-already average over mixed null-and-positive evidence before the credibility discount applies (a
paper/review/rendered.txt-168-limitation noted below). Allocation uncertainty is a Dirichlet with concentration 60 around the
--
paper/review/rendered.txt-175-part; the levels are judgment, proposed by a language model and reviewed by the author, and
paper/review/rendered.txt-176-the results section reports the full consequence of disagreeing with them.
paper/review/rendered.txt-177-Health effects arrive in different natural units — lives saved, life-years, depression-free days —
paper/review/rendered.txt-178-and are converted to discounted QALYs at a 3% annual rate under source-specific conventions:
paper/review/rendered.txt:179:adult mortality anchors sample roughly 26 remaining life-years at a utility draw centered near
paper/review/rendered.txt:180:0.78, the frontier’s child-mortality benchmark uses a fixed ~65 remaining years at utility 0.87, and
paper/review/rendered.txt-181-direct cost-per-QALY anchors keep their sources’ conventions. Every parameter’s unit and dollar
paper/review/rendered.txt-182-vintage is machine-validated at load. The global-health frontier benchmark is handicapped within
paper/review/rendered.txt:183:the same framework: GiveWell’s reported recent program averages (GiveWell 2026), converted
paper/review/rendered.txt-184-to roughly $175–$241 per discounted QALY-equivalent under this model’s own conventions (a
paper/review/rendered.txt:185:model conversion, not a GiveWell QALY figure), modeled as loguniform $150–$260, sharing each
paper/review/rendered.txt:186:draw’s realization multiplier, and receiving RCT-grade credibility — the strongest tier — where
paper/review/rendered.txt-187-portfolio archetypes receive their own.
