paper/review/rendered.txt-562-4.2 Against the global-health frontier
paper/review/rendered.txt:563:Handicapped with the same realization and credibility discounts, the GiveWell-derived frontier
paper/review/rendered.txt-564-benchmark delivers roughly 521× more health per marginal dollar than the blended portfolio;
paper/review/rendered.txt-565-the same sum directed entirely to the frontier would imply on the order of 105.5 million QALYs.
paper/review/rendered.txt-566-That figure is arithmetic, not a forecast, and not an attainable counterfactual: frontier-priced
paper/review/rendered.txt:567:opportunities are scarce — GiveWell’s directed funding runs to hundreds of millions of dollars per
paper/review/rendered.txt:568:year, not tens of billions (GiveWell 2026) — and funding beyond identified room drives toward
paper/review/rendered.txt:569:cash-transfer cost-effectiveness, whose GiveWell estimate rose 3–4× in a 2024 re-evaluation
paper/review/rendered.txt:570:(GiveWell 2024). Converting the full portfolio at cash-transfer cost-effectiveness under this
paper/review/rendered.txt:571:model’s own conventions leaves a multiple in the tens — roughly 20–40×, model arithmetic
paper/review/rendered.txt:572:rather than a GiveWell figure. The defensible statement is directional: the frontier multiple is
paper/review/rendered.txt:573:several hundred at today’s margin and remains large under any diminishing-returns account
paper/review/rendered.txt-574-consistent with these benchmarks.
