paper/index.qmd-191-## Where it comes from
paper/index.qmd-192-
paper/index.qmd:193:@tbl-cause decomposes the mean estimate by cause. The result is the paper's central contrast: the global health and development slice — `{python} F["abroad_share_1"]` of dollars — contributes `{python} F["gh_share"]` of estimated QALYs, at a modeled cost of about `{python} F2["gh_cpq"]` per QALY against `{python} F2["ev_lo"]`–`{python} F2["ev_hi"]` for the causes with quasi-experimental or better U.S. evidence. The `{python} F2["spread"]`-fold spread in modeled cost-effectiveness within a single donor's portfolio, under stipulated priors, is partly the lens speaking — its low end is dominated by assumption-tier buckets whose near-zero credibility is an input, and whose main benefits QALYs do not count — but the spread among evidenced health buckets alone exceeds an order of magnitude, restating in one column an empirical regularity long emphasized in the effective-altruism literature [@ord2013]: the cheapest health in the world is not bought where most philanthropic dollars are spent.
