160-Our cost-per-output estimates are based on financial and programmatic
161-information from our Top Charities. When estimating total outputs
162:attributed to a specific amount of funding (e.g., how many nets will
163:$100 deliver?), we divide the total funding by our estimate of how much
164-it costs to deliver that output (e.g., how much it costs to deliver an
165-insecticide-treated net).
166-
167-For both outcome and output estimates, we use a weighted average of the
168:cost-effectiveness for funds we directed to specific funding
169:opportunities funded from 2022 through 2024. We use a weighted average
170-because both cost per output and cost per outcome vary among programs we
171:recommend funding for. For example, we made both of the grants below to
172:Malaria Consortium’s seasonal malaria chemoprevention program in March
173:2024:
174-
175-- $9.9M to distribute malaria medication in Borno, Nigeria at a cost of
176-  $6 per child treated with a full course of medicine, resulting in an
177:  estimated cost-effectiveness of around $3,500 per life saved
178-- $2.0M to distribute malaria medication in Togo at a cost of $12 per
179-  child treated with a full course of medicine, resulting in an
180:  estimated cost-effectiveness of $6,500 per life saved
181-
182-Cost-per-life-saved estimates have been rounded up to the nearest $500,
183-and cost per output estimates have been rounded to the nearest dollar.
184-Our impact estimates include a weighted average of all grants we made to
185:each program. You can see a list of the specific funding opportunities
186-used in these calculations by looking at grants approved in February
187-2022 through January 2025 in this spreadsheet. We categorize grants by
188-year according to the date we decided to make or recommend them, not the
189-date funds were disbursed. Our impact numbers don’t include all funds we
190:direct to our Top Charities. More detail on this below.
