232:What funding does GiveWell look at to calculate cost-effectiveness?
233-
234:Funds directed to our Top Charities by GiveWell can be grouped in four
235-buckets:
236-
237-1.  Grants we make from our Top Charities Fund and All Grants Fund to
238:    specific funding opportunities
239:2.  Grants we make from GiveWell’s pool of unrestricted funding. See our
240-    excess assets policy
241:3.  Donations we recommend large donors make to specific funding
242-    opportunities
243-4.  Donations that donors make to an organization we recommend, but that
244:    aren’t directed to a specific funding opportunity. This includes
245-    donations made to organizations through our donation portal,
246:    donations made directly to the organizations, and donations through
247-    other third-party organizations that share GiveWell’s
248-    recommendations (e.g., One for the World).
249-
250:We calculate the cost-effectiveness of specific funding opportunities,
251:not the cost-effectiveness of all the funding an organization uses.
252-Because of this, we are only using buckets 1 through 3 as the basis for
253-calculating the cost-effectiveness numbers we’re using in our impact
254:estimates. This constitutes the majority of the total funding we direct
255-to each Top Charity.
256-
257:We exclude the funding in bucket 4 from our impact calculations because
258-we don’t have estimates of the cost-effectiveness of those donations. We
259:only calculate the cost-effectiveness for specific funding
260:opportunities. Funding directed to our Top Charities could be either
261:more or less cost-effective than the funding directed to specific
262:funding gaps. Rather than guessing at a number and using it for our
263:calculations, we’ve excluded this funding.
264-
265-We also exclude grants for which we don’t generate a cost-effectiveness
266-estimate. For example, we do not estimate the cost-effectiveness of
267-grants for monitoring surveys to assess the success of programs. These
268:improve our decision-making ability, but don’t have a direct impact.
269-
270:We do include these types of funding in our lifetime impact estimates
271-(see above).
272-
273:What are funding opportunities?
274-
275:GiveWell makes its decisions about where to recommend funding based on
276:estimates of the cost-effectiveness of specific “funding opportunities”
277-rather than the entire portfolio of an organization’s work.
278-
279:A funding opportunity is generally defined as a specific intervention
280-(e.g., seasonal malaria chemoprevention) in a specific country, although
281:funding opportunities may also be defined at the subnational level.
282-
283:Our cost-effectiveness estimates can differ between funding
284:opportunities. For example, in our April 2024 cost-effectiveness
285:analysis for Malaria Consortium’s seasonal malaria chemoprevention
286-program, we estimated that the program in Burkina Faso was roughly twice
287-as cost-effective as its work in Chad, largely driven by higher rates of
288-malaria mortality in Burkina Faso.
289-
290:Why does GiveWell calculate cost-effectiveness at the funding opportunity level?
291-
292:We analyze individual funding opportunities rather than programs or
293-organizations as a whole because we believe it allows us to better
294:distinguish between different uses of marginal funding. If we directed
295:funding based solely on a single organization-level cost-effectiveness
296:estimate, our analysis would result in recommending funding to only one
297-organization.
298-
299-We believe that would be misleading and would lead to less
300-cost-effective grant-making. By estimating cost-effectiveness at a more
301:granular level, we are better able to recommend funding to multiple
302:organizations with specific funding opportunities that meet or exceed
303-our cost-effectiveness threshold. We use these estimates to decide how
304:to allocate funding from the Top Charities Fund.
305-
306:As well as estimating the cost-effectiveness of specific funding
307-opportunities, we also present aggregate cost-effectiveness estimates
308-for each program on our Top Charities page.
309-
310-How are numbers rounded?
311-
312:You can see a list of the specific funding opportunities used in these
313-calculations here.
314-
315:The cost-effectiveness estimates we share for specific funding
316-opportunities don’t exactly match the numbers we’ve shared in the table
317-above. We’ve rounded the numbers to avoid giving a false sense of
318-precision.
