  # Global-health frontier, expressed as a QALY-equivalent cost with the
  # conversion arithmetic explicit (GiveWell reports lives saved, not QALYs).
  # Denominated at the 3% reference discount rate; when the model runs at a
  # different rate, it rescales this cost by the ratio of the child QALE at 3%
  # to the child QALE at that rate (frontier_child below), keeping the
  # frontier comparison like-for-like at any discount setting.
  frontier_cost_per_qaly_usd:
    dist: loguniform
    low: 150
    high: 260
    unit: usd_per_qaly
    dollars_base_year: 2026
    source: >-
      Derived from [GiveWell's current impact estimates](https://www.givewell.org/impact-estimates)
      of cost per life saved, 2022-2024 program averages: ~$4,000 (Malaria
      Consortium seasonal chemoprevention) to ~$5,500 (AMF nets), figures
      GiveWell rounds up to the nearest $500. Treating those as ~2023 dollars
      and inflating by [CPI-U](https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS)
      335.123/304.702 = 1.10 gives ~$4,400-$6,050 per life. A child death
      averted at ~age 1 with ~65 remaining life-years, discounted at 3% with
      half-cycle correction (annuity ~28.9) and utility ~0.87, is ~25.1
      discounted QALYs, giving endpoints of ~$175-$241 per QALY-equivalent;
      the loguniform {150, 260} widens that for conversion uncertainty
      (utility, remaining years, price level). An earlier revision also used a
      2015 AMF figure ($3,340/life, itself already a discounted-QALY-era
      calculation, in ~2015 dollars); it is retired here in favor of
      GiveWell's current program averages.

  # Fixed conversion inputs for the frontier's life -> QALY arithmetic and its
  # discount-rate rescaling. Author calibration: ~65 remaining years for an
  # under-5 death averted in AMF/Malaria Consortium countries; utility ~0.87
  # near global population norms.
  frontier_child:
    remaining_life_years: {dist: fixed, value: 65, unit: years}
    utility_weight: {dist: fixed, value: 0.87, unit: utility_weight}

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TWO ORTHOGONAL ADJUSTMENTS (GiveWell-style), kept deliberately separate:
#
#   causal_credibility (per archetype, below) — IS THE MEASURED EFFECT REAL?

  global_health:
    label: "Global health & development (non-US delivery)"
    allocation_share: 0.048
    method: cost_per_qaly
    causal_credibility: strong_quasi
    identification: >-
      Dollars route here by delivery geography: the non-US share of each
      organization's reported service locations, applied to its
      health-relevant focus areas (src/msqaly/allocation.py). The routed
      portfolio spans GiveWell-grade programs backed by RCTs (Malaria
      Consortium $10M, Evidence Action $20M, GiveDirectly's global program
      $50M+$5M) through strong community-health-worker and health-systems
      organizations (Living Goods $25M+$3.5M, Muso $15M, Amref $50M,
      Partners In Health $50M, Noora Health $20M, icddr,b $16M) to
      partial-health-tagged organizations. strong_quasi reflects that mix.
    cost_per_qaly_usd: {dist: lognormal_ci, low: 300, high: 4000, unit: usd_per_qaly, dollars_base_year: 2026}
    source: >-
      Pricing a non-US health dollar at US anchors understates it by orders
      of magnitude — the correction a reader prompted. The 90% CI $300-$4,000
      per QALY (2026$) spans
      [GiveWell's current program averages](https://www.givewell.org/impact-estimates)
      (~$4,000-5,500 per under-5 life saved ~ $175-241 per discounted QALY,
      the marquee floor sitting just below this range's low end),
      community-health-worker and systems programs GiveWell scores in the
      low single-digit multiples of cash (~$500-2,000 per QALY-equivalent),
      and [GiveDirectly's global cash program](https://blog.givewell.org/2024/11/12/re-evaluating-the-impact-of-unconditional-cash-transfers/)
      (child-mortality channel ~ $8,000 per discounted QALY, above this
      range's high end — the tail covers it). Gift amounts verified in
      [Yield Giving's database](https://yieldgiving.com/gifts).

  econ_cash:
    label: "Economic security - cash & financial"
    allocation_share: 0.029
    method: cost_per_qaly
    causal_credibility: strong_quasi
    identification: >-
      Mixed by target population, replicated across developed countries.
      Adult-targeted cash is credibly ~null on health (Swedish lottery
      randomization; two US cash RCTs; Swedish lottery wealth buys sustained
      life satisfaction but significantly smaller mental-health effects).
      Child-targeted cash shows replicated positive effects in strong
      quasi-experimental designs in the US (Mothers' Pensions, EITC, casino
      dividends) and Canada (child-benefit expansions). strong_quasi
      reflects that the positive anchors are QEDs coexisting with RCT-grade
      adult nulls.
    cost_per_qaly_usd: {dist: lognormal_ci, low: 50000, high: 1500000, unit: usd_per_qaly, dollars_base_year: 2026}
    source: >-
      [Cesarini et al. (2016, QJE)](https://academic.oup.com/qje/article/131/2/687/2606947)
      lottery study finds ~zero causal effect of income on adult mortality in a
      rich country; the largest US guaranteed-income RCT
      ([Miller et al. 2024, NBER w32711](https://www.nber.org/papers/w32711):
      $1,000/month for 3 years) found no physical-health effects and fading
      first-year stress/mental-health gains; a one-time $500-$2,000 UCT RCT
      with 5,243 Americans in poverty
      ([Jaroszewicz et al. 2024](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4154000))
      found no improvement on any pre-specified financial, psychological, or
      health outcome. Child-targeted cash shows real effects in strong
      quasi-experimental designs, anchoring the low end:
      [Aizer, Eli, Ferrie & Lleras-Muney (2016, AER)](https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.20140529)
      Mothers' Pensions ($10-30/month, typically 3 years: ~$360-1,080
      nominal 1910s-30s ~ $7k-20k in 2026$ per family via CPI x~18.6)
      raised accepted applicants' sons' longevity ~1 year (1.5 for the
      poorest; daughters unobserved) — ~$7k-20k per undiscounted life-year,
      ~$50k-115k per discounted QALY (3%, ~65-year lag, 0.78 utility);
      [Hoynes, Miller & Simon (2015, AEJ:Policy)](https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/pol.20120179)
      $1,000 of EITC (treatment-on-treated) cuts low-birth-weight incidence
      2-3% (6.7-10.8% for single low-education mothers);
      [Great Smoky Mountains casino dividends](https://www.nber.org/papers/w24337)
      (~$6k/year/household) cut child behavioral problems ~40%, with
      depression/anxiety reductions persisting to age 30;
      [Milligan & Stabile (2011, AEJ:Policy)](https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/pol.3.3.175)
      Canadian child-benefit expansions (province x time x family-type
      variation) improve child test scores, child mental health, and
      maternal health. On the adult quality-of-life channel,
      [Lindqvist, Ostling & Cesarini (2020, REStud)](https://academic.oup.com/restud/article/87/6/2703/5734654)
      find Swedish lottery wealth yields sustained life-satisfaction gains
      but significantly smaller happiness and mental-health effects. Broader
      [EITC health evidence](https://academyhealth.org/sites/default/files/Updated.EITC%20Rapid%20Evidence%20Review%20FINAL.pdf)
      beyond these designs stays mixed and confounded. Prior US $/QALY
      estimates exist and run far lower at face value:
      [Muennig et al. (2016, AJPM)](https://www.ajpmonline.org/article/S0749-3797(16)30249-5/abstract)
      put state EITC supplements at $7,786/QALY (95% CI $4,100-$13,400) via
      an interrupted time series on BRFSS self-reported health, and a
      [2024 VA analysis](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC11539017/)
      put temporary financial assistance at $22,676/QALY. Those designs are
      what the credibility axis discounts; this prior's low end deliberately
      starts at the hard-endpoint Aizer anchor instead, so a reader who
      takes the ITS as causal should treat this range as too conservative.
      The lognormal $50k-$1.5M (2026$) spans child-targeted-QED optimism to
      adult-null pessimism; most cash value remains non-health consumption
      and wellbeing, which QALYs do not capture.

