web/params.json:233:      "identification": "Mixed by target population, replicated across developed countries. Adult-targeted cash is credibly ~null on health (Swedish lottery randomization; two US cash RCTs; Swedish lottery wealth buys sustained life satisfaction but significantly smaller mental-health effects). Child-targeted cash shows replicated positive effects in strong quasi-experimental designs in the US (Mothers' Pensions, EITC, casino dividends) and Canada (child-benefit expansions). strong_quasi reflects that the positive anchors are QEDs coexisting with RCT-grade adult nulls.",
web/params.json:241:      "source": "[Cesarini et al. (2016, QJE)](https://academic.oup.com/qje/article/131/2/687/2606947) lottery study finds ~zero causal effect of income on adult mortality in a rich country; the largest US guaranteed-income RCT ([Miller et al. 2024, NBER w32711](https://www.nber.org/papers/w32711): $1,000/month for 3 years) found no physical-health effects and fading first-year stress/mental-health gains; a one-time $500-$2,000 UCT RCT with 5,243 Americans in poverty ([Jaroszewicz et al. 2024](https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4154000)) found no improvement on any pre-specified financial, psychological, or health outcome. Child-targeted cash shows real effects in strong quasi-experimental designs, anchoring the low end: [Aizer, Eli, Ferrie & Lleras-Muney (2016, AER)](https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.20140529) Mothers' Pensions ($10-30/month, typically 3 years: ~$360-1,080 nominal 1910s-30s ~ $7k-20k in 2026$ per family via CPI x~18.6) raised accepted applicants' sons' longevity ~1 year (1.5 for the poorest; daughters unobserved) \u2014 ~$7k-20k per undiscounted life-year, ~$50k-115k per discounted QALY (3%, ~65-year lag, 0.78 utility); [Hoynes, Miller & Simon (2015, AEJ:Policy)](https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/pol.20120179) $1,000 of EITC (treatment-on-treated) cuts low-birth-weight incidence 2-3% (6.7-10.8% for single low-education mothers); [Great Smoky Mountains casino dividends](https://www.nber.org/papers/w24337) (~$6k/year/household) cut child behavioral problems ~40%, with depression/anxiety reductions persisting to age 30; [Milligan & Stabile (2011, AEJ:Policy)](https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/pol.3.3.175) Canadian child-benefit expansions (province x time x family-type variation) improve child test scores, child mental health, and maternal health. On the adult quality-of-life channel, [Lindqvist, Ostling & Cesarini (2020, REStud)](https://academic.oup.com/restud/article/87/6/2703/5734654) find Swedish lottery wealth yields sustained life-satisfaction gains but significantly smaller happiness and mental-health effects. Broader [EITC health evidence](https://academyhealth.org/sites/default/files/Updated.EITC%20Rapid%20Evidence%20Review%20FINAL.pdf) beyond these designs stays mixed and confounded. Prior US $/QALY estimates exist and run far lower at face value: [Muennig et al. (2016, AJPM)](https://www.ajpmonline.org/article/S0749-3797(16)30249-5/abstract) put state EITC supplements at $7,786/QALY (95% CI $4,100-$13,400) via an interrupted time series on BRFSS self-reported health, and a [2024 VA analysis](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC11539017/) put temporary financial assistance at $22,676/QALY. Those designs are what the credibility axis discounts; this prior's low end deliberately starts at the hard-endpoint Aizer anchor instead, so a reader who takes the ITS as causal should treat this range as too conservative. The lognormal $50k-$1.5M (2026$) spans child-targeted-QED optimism to adult-null pessimism; most cash value remains non-health consumption and wellbeing, which QALYs do not capture."
