paper/review/sol/neutrality.round2.log:1033:+Each Monte Carlo draw allocates the giving across archetypes (a Dirichlet centered on the derived shares), assigns each archetype a cost per QALY drawn from a distribution anchored in published estimates, and multiplies the implied QALYs by two independent discounts. **Causal credibility** asks whether the measured effect is real. Each archetype carries the identification tier of its best supporting evidence, and the tier sets a Beta-distributed shrinkage factor toward the null: a lottery-randomized wealth shock [@cesarini2016wealth] or the Medicaid mortality quasi-experiments — the ACA expansions [@miller2021medicaid], with cost–benefit arithmetic from the pre-ACA state expansions [@sommers2017medicaid] whose spending component draws on the Oregon Health Insurance Experiment [@finkelstein2012oregon] — keeps most of its effect; replicated child-targeted cash quasi-experiments [@aizer2016cash] anchor the cash bucket; the community-health-center rollout design [@bailey2015war] and similar contested quasi-experiments keep less; associational and assumption-only categories are shrunk near zero. **Realization** asks whether a marginal philanthropic dollar delivers the studied effect at all — transport to different populations, overhead, and funging, net of possible capacity effects: surveyed Scott recipients report stronger capacity and reach [@cep2023gifts], self-reports on whose basis the model permits realization above one (an author judgment, not a CEP effect estimate). It is one global triangular draw with mode 0.80 on support 0.55–1.10.
paper/review/sol/neutrality.round2.log:1090:-Handicapped with the same realization and credibility discounts, the GiveWell-derived frontier benchmark delivers roughly `{python} F["frontier_mult"]`× more health per marginal dollar than the blended portfolio; the same sum directed entirely to the frontier would imply on the order of `{python} F["frontier_q"]` QALYs. That figure is a marginal comparison, not an attainable counterfactual: frontier-priced opportunities are scarce, GiveWell directs hundreds of millions — not tens of billions — per year at these prices, and funding beyond identified room drives toward cash-transfer cost-effectiveness. Redeploying the full portfolio would compress the multiple toward a floor plausibly under 20–40× [@givewell2024cash]. The honest statement is directional: the frontier multiple is several hundred at today's margin and remains large under any plausible account of diminishing returns.
paper/review/sol/neutrality.round2.log:1091:+Handicapped with the same realization and credibility discounts, the GiveWell-derived frontier benchmark delivers roughly `{python} F["frontier_mult"]`× more health per marginal dollar than the blended portfolio; the same sum directed entirely to the frontier would imply on the order of `{python} F["frontier_q"]` QALYs. That figure is arithmetic, not a forecast, and not an attainable counterfactual: frontier-priced opportunities are scarce — GiveWell's directed funding runs to hundreds of millions of dollars per year, not tens of billions [@givewell2026impact] — and funding beyond identified room drives toward cash-transfer cost-effectiveness, whose GiveWell estimate rose 3–4× in a 2024 re-evaluation [@givewell2024cash]. Converting the full portfolio at cash-transfer cost-effectiveness under this model's own conventions leaves a multiple in the tens — roughly 20–40×, model arithmetic rather than a GiveWell figure. The defensible statement is directional: the frontier multiple is several hundred at today's margin and remains large under any diminishing-returns account consistent with these benchmarks.
paper/review/sol/citations.round2.log:95:The six requested journal records were checked against DOI/publisher metadata. `cesarini2016wealth`, `miller2021medicaid`, `sommers2017medicaid`, `bailey2015war`, and `aizer2016cash` have the correct named authors, year, journal, volume/issue, page span, and DOI; `finkelstein2012oregon` has the correct eight named authors and all other requested fields but omits the corporate coauthor, the Oregon Health Study Group. The manuscript nevertheless needs major citation revision: the megagiving statistic is attached to a temporally incapable and bibliographically misidentified CNBC article, Sommers (2017) is inaccurately grouped with an ACA mortality study despite the exact misattribution warning in `SOURCES.md`, and the GiveWell cash citation does not establish the manuscript's portfolio-scale multiple or diminishing-returns claims. The CEP evidence and HHS valuation are directionally usable after narrower attribution and corrected bibliographic details, while two journal entries are orphaned and several quantitative conventions or literature claims lack in-text support.
paper/review/sol/citations.round2.log:108:   **LOCATION:** Section 4.2, p. 7, “funding beyond identified room drives toward cash-transfer cost-effectiveness” and “the 20–40× range implied by GiveWell's cash-transfer benchmark (GiveWell 2024).”  
paper/review/sol/citations.round2.log:109:   **Problem:** [GiveWell's 2024 post](https://blog.givewell.org/2024/11/12/re-evaluating-the-impact-of-unconditional-cash-transfers/) says that its revised estimate of GiveDirectly's flagship cash program is 3–4 times its *previous estimate* and that GiveWell's current top programs are at least twice as cost-effective as the revised cash estimate. It does not report a 20–40× comparison with Scott's portfolio, does not convert cash-transfer welfare into QALYs, and does not say that tens of billions of additional funding converge to cash-transfer cost-effectiveness. Thus the citation is accurate for the fact of a cash re-evaluation but not for the characterization or numerical range attached to it here.  
paper/review/sol/citations.round2.log:110:   **Concrete fix:** Label 20–40× as an author/model-derived scenario and show the complete like-for-like arithmetic, including how GiveWell's units are translated into health-only QALYs; otherwise remove the range. Cite the 2024 post only for its actual 3–4× re-evaluation. Do not describe cash as an empirically established portfolio-scale “floor” without a source and a unit-comparability argument.
paper/review/sol/citations.round2.log:114:   **Problem:** These are externally checkable claims but no cited source in the manuscript establishes GiveWell's annual directed amount, the amount available at the quoted frontier prices, or a portfolio-scale diminishing-returns curve. `givewell2024cash` does none of those things. Calling the material “cited literature” overstates the citation coverage.  
paper/review/sol/citations.round2.log:115:   **Concrete fix:** Add separate citations to GiveWell's annual metrics/grantmaking totals and its room-for-more-funding or funding-bar methodology, quote the relevant year and amount, and characterize the portfolio-scale compression explicitly as a scenario unless a source quantifies it. If no source supplies a 20–40× curve, delete that precision.
paper/review/sol/citations.round2.log:133:   **LOCATION:** `references.bib`, `finkelstein2012oregon` and `aizer2016cash`; rendered reference list, pp. 11–12.  
paper/review/sol/citations.round2.log:134:   **Problem:** Both entries are uncited in the manuscript and therefore absent from the rendered reference list. Finkelstein et al. (2012) is relevant to the Oregon spending effects used inside Sommers's cost calculation, and Aizer et al. (2016) appears relevant to the cash-transfer archetype, but neither role is stated in the paper. In addition, [DOI metadata for Finkelstein et al.](https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjs020) lists the Oregon Health Study Group after the eight named authors; the BibTeX omits it. All requested fields for [Aizer et al.](https://doi.org/10.1257/aer.20140529) are correct.  
