17-CEGA Technology Program Manager Sam Fishman describes how CEGA’s Cost
18-Transparency Initiative (CTI), which promotes the generation of more and
19:better cost evidence and transparency of cost data, can identify better
20-opportunities for social impact funding.
21-
22-Despite a global pandemic and consequent recession, 2020 saw a record
23-level of charitable giving in the US–$471 billion, representing a 5.1%
24-increase from 2019. For many philanthropic organizations, growing
25-donations have been a pleasant surprise. However, growing budgets also
26:put pressure on donors to find attractive investment opportunities
27-quickly.
28-
29:Many of these donors are looking to cost-effectiveness and cost-benefit
30-analyses to decide how to allocate resources (for example, organizations
31-like GiveWell, IRC, USAID, the Gates Foundation, and GiveDirectly, among
32:others, actively generate cost evidence). But decision-makers need high
33:quality cost and impact evidence to make well-informed decisions about
34:the relative cost-effectiveness of alternative investments. While many
35-organizations, including CEGA and our peer research centers IPA, J-PAL,
36-and 3ie have been working for over a decade to build the impact evidence
37:base, good cost evidence remains lacking in impact evaluation research.
38-
39-Recognizing that every donor has their own internal constraints (such as
40:capacity to review evidence and identify worthwhile investment
41-opportunities), CEGA believes that by significantly bolstering the
42:evidence base on intervention costs, donors could much more quickly and
43:easily identify cost-effective opportunities for investing burgeoning
44-charitable contributions.
45-
46-Through our Cost Transparency Initiative, CEGA promotes the generation
47:of more and better cost evidence and transparency of cost data, as one
48-route to identifying better opportunities for social impact funding. We
49:seek to make three key improvements to the cost evidence ecosystem: 1)
50:expand cost evidence production in new sectors, 2) produce larger, and
51:more comparable datasets with cost evidence, and 3) diversify cost
52-methods.
53-
54-  Filling this gap isn’t just an academic research objective–it can
55:  change how philanthropies identify, and choose, investment
56-  opportunities.
57-
58-Support Cost Evidence in New Sectors
59-
60:Many of the most cost-effective interventions we know about are in the
61-health sector. For example, five of GiveWell’s top six recommended
62-charities are health interventions (bed nets, malaria treatments,
63-deworming, immunization incentives, and vitamin A supplements) where as
64-little as $3,000-$4,500 can save a life. Besides the fact that saving a
65-life has a particularly high value, the bias towards global health can
66-be attributed partly to the fact that health interventions are more
67:likely to have produced cost-effectiveness data in the first place. The
68-health sector has a few decades’ head-start over other sectors in
69:rigorously measuring the cost-effectiveness of interventions, in part
70-because major health institutions have effectively integrated
71:cost-evidence production into their decision making processes. With the
72-notable exception of education (where improvements in evaluation
73:methods and metrics have also emerged), cost evidence still lags
74-significantly behind in other sectors.
75-
76-Health interventions will likely maintain advantages in
77:cost-effectiveness due to the high stakes involved. However, if there
78:were more cost-effectiveness evidence in other sectors, there might be
79:more investment opportunities on the menu for donors with broad sectoral
80:interests. For example, other highly cost-effective programs might
81-emerge in information and communication technology, governance,
82-agriculture, and elsewhere that could give donors more options in any
83-given year to invest in scaling exciting programs.
--
85-Build Bigger Cost Datasets
86-
87-One of the challenges donors and other decision-makers face is a lack of
88:large, comparable datasets. Most of the cost data that exists in LMIC
89-settings — which is typically pulled from program expenditures,
90-monitoring and evaluation data, and institutional knowledge — is
91-collected by implementing organizations using idiosyncratic finance
92-reporting systems, making it more difficult to make comparison of
93-similar programs implemented by different organizations (additionally,
94:many organizations have an incentive to distort costs to highlight
95-efficiencies). But fixing these issues and building comparable datasets
96:is critical. Cost-effectiveness analysis (costs and outcomes) and
97:cost-efficiency analysis (costs and outputs) are both inherently
98-comparative exercises, so the more data points we have and the more
99-standardized the collection process, the more relevant insights we can
100-derive.
101-
102-One key way to address this challenge is to increase coordination in the
103:production of cost evidence among the producers of impact evaluations.
104-CEGA’s Costing Community of Practice (CCoP) is in part an effort to
105:increase coordination between key producers of cost evidence in LMICs by
106:generating regular discussions around comparative approaches to cost
107-collection and analysis.
108-
109:The rewards to larger cost-effectiveness and cost-efficiency datasets
110-aren’t only about offering more options to choose. More data points for
111-comparison can provide a more nuanced understanding of how
112:cost-effectiveness or cost-efficiency might change at different levels
113-of scale, over time, across contexts, and across design features. For
114-example, during our Cost-ober 2021 workshop, the International Rescue
115:Committee (IRC) shared a cost-efficiency dataset on the costs of cash
116-transfer programs that was large enough to allow IRC to see how factors
117-like delivery method, targeting, scale, design, and geographic context
118:contributed to cost-efficiency of the program.
119-
120-Diversify Methodologies For Comparison
121-
122:There is no one-size-fits-all approach to comparing the costs and
123:impacts of alternative interventions. Donors can expand their investment
124-options, and invest more effectively, by leveraging the most appropriate
125-types of methods for comparison to support the specific decisions they
126-are making. CEGA is working to expand this toolbox, and ensure that
127:costing methods are better tailored to organizations with different
128:interests, philosophies, revenues, and investment timelines. Two of the
129-approaches we’re exploring, which were highlighted at our Cost-ober
130-event in 2021, are described below.
131-
132-Cash Benchmarking
133-
134:A lot of development programs claim to be cost-effective, but
135:cost-effective compared to what? Cash benchmarking asks “If an
136:intervention isn’t at least as cost-effective as cash — which is easily
137-distributed and impacts a wide range of outcomes — then why even bother
138-investing in it?”
139-
140:The cash benchmarking approach puts cost evidence into an intuitive
141:systematic framework for decision-making. While not appropriate in all
142-settings, organizations that might genuinely consider cash as an
143:alternative investment vehicle are probably best suited to using cash
144-benchmarking for evidence-informed decision-making.
145-
146-Portfolio-level Cost Analysis
147-
148-USAID has experimented using Social Rate of Return (SROR) for evaluating
149:the Development Innovation Ventures (DIV) Portfolio. They found that
150:four innovations drove the whole portfolio’s success, producing $5 for
151:every dollar invested, for a 77% social rate of return (SROR) for the
152:portfolio. CEGA is now exploring a similar portfolio level SROR approach
153-with another donor exploring scalable innovations.
154-
155-This approach hedges against the risk of failure by diversifying

