# Neutrality review — round 2

I checked each round-1 neutrality finding against the canonical fresh render (`paper/review/rendered.txt`), the manuscript source, and the cited/repository material where relevant. The response marks all twelve neutrality findings adopted; none was declined or deferred.

## Round-1 finding resolution

| Round-1 finding | Status | Verification note |
|---:|---|---|
| 1 | RESOLVED | §4.1 now calls the decomposition the paper's “central contrast,” consistently labels the quantities estimated/modeled, and no longer calls the model output a fact. |
| 2 | RESOLVED | The author footnote and acknowledgments now disclose that neither the author nor the organizations he leads have received funding from MacKenzie Scott or Yield Giving. |
| 3 | RESOLVED | The identified abstract and introduction formulations now use “estimated impact,” “accounts for,” and “estimates” rather than presenting the modeled output as an observed fact. |
| 4 | PARTIALLY RESOLVED | The abstract and §5.1 body narrow the comparison to single distributional parameters and expressly concede that structural choices can move the headline more, but the §5.1 heading still says “Evidence philosophy dominates everything else,” contradicting that qualification; narrow the heading too. |
| 5 | RESOLVED | §4.1 labels the 1,278-fold result a modeled spread under stipulated priors, explains that the low end partly reflects the QALY lens and near-zero credibility inputs, and separately reports the evidenced-health comparison. |
| 6 | RESOLVED | The effective-altruism characterization is softened to a regularity “long emphasized” and is now linked to the canonical Ord (2013) cost-effectiveness essay in text and bibliography. |
| 7 | PARTIALLY RESOLVED | §4.2 now labels 20–40× as model arithmetic, ties it to the cited GiveWell benchmarks, replaces “honest,” and disclaims attainability; however, “under any diminishing-returns account consistent with these benchmarks” remains an unsupported universal because the benchmarks do not identify behavior at the full $30.3 billion scale. |
| 8 | RESOLVED | §5.1 replaces the seminar flourish and “claimed” with the neutral description “evidence below randomized or strong quasi-experimental identification standards.” |
| 9 | RESOLVED | §2.2 now says Scott publishes “something more granular,” removing the evaluative praise. |
| 10 | RESOLVED | The introduction now qualifies the priority claim with “to my knowledge,” and the contribution claim is further narrowed to what the author believes is the first outside portfolio-level estimate. |
| 11 | RESOLVED | The conclusion now limits transferability to givers with comparable gift-level disclosure and separately identifies public grant listings as the foundation analogue. |
| 12 | RESOLVED | §2.2 now conditions representativeness explicitly: “under the imputation model.” |

## New findings

None. The fresh regression pass found no neutrality problem introduced by the round-1 edits beyond the two incompletely narrowed formulations above.

RECOMMENDATION: Minor revisions

