+# Citations referee report — round 2
+
+I checked each round-1 finding against the canonical fresh render, `paper/index.qmd`, `paper/references.bib`, `SOURCES.md`, `data/parameters.yaml`, and the cited sources. The response marks all nine citation findings adopted; none of this referee's findings was declined or deferred.
+
+## Resolution of round-1 findings
+
+| Round-1 finding | Status | Note |
+|---:|---|---|
+| 1 | **RESOLVED** | The abstract now says one-third of 2025 U.S. megagift *value*, and the introduction gives the supported $6.65B/$19.2B comparison with Giving USA/AP while reserving CNBC for Yield Giving's $7.17B annual total; CNBC's author and title are corrected. |
+| 2 | **RESOLVED** | The text now separates Miller et al.'s ACA-expansion mortality design from Sommers's cost–benefit reanalysis of pre-ACA expansions and cites Finkelstein for the OHIE spending component. |
+| 3 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | GiveWell (2024) is now attached only to its actual 3–4× re-evaluation, and 20–40× is labeled model arithmetic, but the paper still shows neither the cash-to-QALY input nor the arithmetic producing that range; `data/parameters.yaml` contains related assumptions but does not transparently reproduce the manuscript's 20–40× interval. |
+| 4 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The cited GiveWell impact page does support “several hundred million dollars” of annual recommended grants and explains marginal funding, but it does not establish that funding beyond identified room converges to cash-transfer cost-effectiveness or that the multiple remains large under *any* diminishing-returns account consistent with the benchmarks. Those remain portfolio-scale scenario claims. |
+| 5 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The false “common set of conventions” description has been replaced by an accurate adult/child/direct-anchor split, but the manuscript still gives no in-text support for the 26-year/0.78 adult calibration, the 65-year/0.87 child calibration, or the normative 3% rate; the parameter file itself labels the child figures author calibration and supplies no authoritative child sources. |
+| 6 | **RESOLVED** | The CEP entry now has the named authors and exact title, and the prose accurately limits the evidence to surveyed recipients' self-reports while identifying realization above one as author judgment rather than a CEP estimate. |
+| 7 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The ASPE entry and main results attribution are corrected and Table 3 is identified, but the manuscript does not disclose that the sampled HHS values are CPI-adjusted from constant 2025 dollars to May-2026 dollars, and the conclusion still broadens an HHS regulatory-analysis recommendation to “the government's own regulatory valuation.” |
+| 8 | **RESOLVED** | Finkelstein and Aizer are now cited in text, the Oregon Health Study Group is present in the BibTeX author list, and neither entry is orphaned. |
+| 9 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | `SOURCES.md` now correctly says 14 archetypes, and Ord is cited for large cross-intervention cost-effectiveness differences; Ord does not by itself document the separate claim about where most philanthropic dollars are spent, so that half of the sentence remains unsupported as a literature attribution. |
+
+## New findings from the regression pass
+
+1. **SEVERITY: MINOR**  
+   **LOCATION:** Introduction, rendered p. 1, citation shown as “Gamboa 2026”; `paper/references.bib`, `ap2026givingusa`.  
+   **Problem:** The AP/Chronicle page names Rasheeda Childress, not Glenn Gamboa. Its page title is “Donors gave U.S. charities $617 billion in 2025, according to the new Giving USA report” (the HTML title is “Philanthropic donations hit $617B in 2025, says Giving USA 2026”), not the title in the BibTeX entry. The page does support $6.65B against $19.2B, so the quantitative claim is sound but the reference is misidentified.  
+   **Fix:** Change the author to Rasheeda Childress and use the publisher's displayed title (plus the June 23, 2026 publication date).
+
+2. **SEVERITY: MINOR**  
+   **LOCATION:** `paper/references.bib`, `givewell2026impact`, `robinhood2025`, `constellation2025`, and `cega2023div`; rendered references pp. 13–14.  
+   **Problem:** Several web references added in the revision use an access/reporting year as though it were the publication year. GiveWell's page says published November 2021 and last updated November 2025, not 2026; Robin Hood's structured metadata says published 2023 and modified 2024, not 2025; Constellation's *2025 Investment Report* page says published February 27, 2026; and the CEGA page is dated March 18, 2022, not 2023. The claims these pages support are otherwise accurately characterized.  
+   **Fix:** Use each page's publication or last-update year as appropriate and put July 2026 only in an access-date field/note. For CEGA, also add the named author shown by the page if the chosen citation style permits it.
+
+3. **SEVERITY: MINOR**  
+   **LOCATION:** Model, rendered p. 3, “replicated child-targeted cash quasi-experiments (Aizer et al. 2016) anchor the cash bucket.”  
+   **Problem:** Aizer et al. is one quasi-experimental study of the Mothers' Pension program. It supports a child-targeted cash anchor, but by itself does not support the plural “replicated ... quasi-experiments” characterization; the additional studies discussed in `data/parameters.yaml` are not cited here or included in the paper bibliography.  
+   **Fix:** Either write “a child-targeted cash quasi-experiment” or cite the additional quasi-experimental replications underlying the plural claim.
+
+RECOMMENDATION: Minor revisions

